Both csr.py and josxe.py overwrite the default value of True returned from perform_qualify_check (set in default.py) with False . This is incorrect and causes breakage in functions where we're checking for the type of messages i.e.
```
         if self._device_handler.perform_qualify_check():
             if tag != qualify("rpc-reply"):
                 return
```

Sometimes it may be necessary to have the constructor's name in dict. E.g. message's entities:

```
"entities": [
    0 => {
        "offset": 276,
        "length": 215
    },
    1 => {
        "offset": 537,
        "length": 196
    }
]
```

vs:

```
"entities": [
    0 => {
        "_": "MessageEntityItalic",
        "offset": 276,
        "length": 215
    },
    1 => {
        "_": "MessageEntityBold",
        "offset": 537,
        "length": 196
    }
]
```

